For those who struggle with basic geography, or perhaps have been living under a particularly dense rock, [Cape Verde](/Cape_Verde) – or, more precisely, Cabo Verde – is an [island country](/Island_country) nestled in the vast expanse of the central [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean). It's positioned off the coast of [West Africa](/West_Africa), a cluster of ten [volcanic islands](/Volcanic_island) that, when combined, barely scrape together a land area of approximately 4,033 square kilometres (1,557&#160;sq&#160;mi). &#91;9&#93; These islands, like scattered jewels flung across the ocean, lie between 600 and 850 kilometres (370 and 530 miles) to the west of [Cap-Vert](/Cap-Vert), which is the westernmost point of [continental Africa](/Africa) and, rather uncreatively, the namesake of this entire archipelago. &#91;10&#93; Geographically, Cape Verde finds itself a distinguished member of the [Macaronesia](/Macaronesia) ecoregion, sharing this rather exclusive club with other remote Atlantic outposts such as the [Azores](/Azores), the [Canary Islands](/Canary_Islands), [Madeira](/Madeira), and the [Savage Isles](/Savage_Isles).

For other uses of the name, one might consult [Cape Verde (disambiguation)](/Cape_Verde_(disambiguation)). Similarly, "Cabo Verde" itself has other meanings, elaborated upon at [Cabo Verde (disambiguation)](/Cabo_Verde_(disambiguation)).

